<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Senior AI Engineer with a hardware background, exploring LLM optimisation on RISC-V"
>
  <div class="page">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm Paddy McNabb — a Senior AI Engineer with a Ph.D. in Power System Dynamics and a first-class
      M.Eng in Electronics &amp; Electrical Engineering from the University of Edinburgh. That hardware
      foundation has always sat beneath everything I do in software, and it's what draws me back to
      the metal when most AI engineers are happy to stay in the cloud.
    </p>

    <p>
      Over 19 years I've built production AI and ML systems across Energy, Financial Services, and the
      Public Sector — from world-first inertia forecasting platforms at GE Digital and National Grid,
      to ML deployment infrastructure at NatWest, to document automation systems processing land
      registry submissions at Registers of Scotland. I've spent a lot of time thinking about
      performance at scale: terabyte-scale data pipelines, sub-second API response times, 99.9% uptime
      systems.
    </p>

    <p>
      That instinct for low-level performance is what led me to RISC-V. My electronics background
      means I'm comfortable reasoning about what's happening at the ISA level — register pressure,
      instruction counts, memory bandwidth — not just what a framework reports. I'm particularly
      interested in running and optimising large language models on RISC-V hardware, and in how RISC-V
      integrates with accelerators like vector processing units and NPUs to change the inference
      performance equation.
    </p>

    <p>
      This blog is where I document that work — rigorous, multi-scale evaluation of LLM performance
      on RISC-V, from classic benchmarks down to microarchitectural profiling. The goal is always to
      understand exactly where performance is won or lost, and to make decisions grounded in data at
      every level of the stack.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: 760px;
